	abstract = {Integrated research across biological scales is vital to understand and anticipate the impacts of global change on ecosystem function and biodiversity.  There is now a plethora of ecological, natural history, climate, and remotely sensed data available to address this important issue.   Integrating these disparate (and often ‘messy’) datasets into models across spatial, temporal, and biological scales is tantalizing but perilous.  Using examples ranging from fire ecology in South Africa to three-toed woodpecker distributions in North America to high resolution maps of global cloud cover, I will discuss several important challenges that must be addressed to rigorously harness these data streams (and keep track of their uncertainties) for scientific progress and prudent decision-making.},
